processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Minimal processing, 2018. Some records remain in original file folders.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC.

When requesting to view audiovisual material, please refer to the Title and the AV Number (example: AV 1916). Researchers are asked to check the "Restrictions" note for each Title. If a Title does not currently have an access copy, please contact a RAC archivist for further instruction.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: RAC has legal title, copyright and literary property rights to this collection in so far as it holds them.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series documents the administration of the International Program in Health Care Policy (IHP) including records documenting symposiums, conferences and workshops, program planning, correspondence and reports and chronological files, as well as records of the associated fellowship programs including the Harkness Fellowships, Atlantic Fellowships and Ian Axford (New Zealand) Fellowships. The bulk of the material represented in this series spans the 1990s through the early 2000s.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The Commonwealth Fund records were donated to RAC in 1985. The initial transfer of archival records to RAC began in 1986, and transfers continue on a regular basis. This series was transferred to RAC as multiple accessions from 2007 through 2009.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center recognizes that our audiovisual materials may contain problematic language and/or content.

The films, videos, and/or sound in this collection have not been altered in any way. All titles and/or content are illustrative of the creator's original vision. As such, this audiovisual collection may contain discriminatory visual and/or aural content that is representative of racial, gendered, or ableist biases.

Accompanying description, most often with creator or donor-generated language and terminology, has to this point been retained and maintained "as received" by RAC with minimal archivist intervention or augmentation.
We acknowledge these problems and aim to cultivate inclusive representation and equity by reconsidering and enhancing our description of this audiovisual material with current sensibilities.

scopecontent.p: Continuation of Bioterrorism One Year Later talk. Topics include small pox vaccines, working with Congress to improve local publich health systems, state laboratory communication with the CDC, preparations for the 2000 Sydney Olympics, the September 11th attacks, and the 2002 Bali Bombings. DA Henderson and Tommy Thompson speak about emergency management arrangements.

did.unittitle: International Symposium on Health Care Policy (5)

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Health Care Quality Indicators Working Group. Topics include rising helath care costs, stat on health care quality and outcomes. 36 minutes into the recording a new talk brings, "The Pharmaceutical Dilemma: Controlling Costs, Improving Quality and Ensuring Access" by Alan Maynard.

did.unittitle: International Symposium on Health Care Policy (6)

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Continuation of "Pharmaceutical Dilemma"by Alan Maynard with a focus on the United Kingdom and the cost for medical services.

did.unittitle: International Symposium on Health Care Policy (7)

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: 9 minutes into the recording a new talk begins, roundtable observations of medical care in the United States, topics include prescription drug use and administration.

did.unittitle: International Symposium on Health Care Policy (8)

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Balancing hospital costs with the needto invest in quality improvements, information technology and nursing in Canada. 24 minutes into the recording a new talk begins on technological change and its contributions to health care and hospital costs.
